[Student "W"]
{[showcards W:SA E:S9,S3 S:S5,S8]

You are West. The bidding has been as shown. You led the \SA, East plays the \S9, South the \S5. You assume East has signaled you to continue \Ss, so you play the \SQ. On this trick East plays the \S3 and South the \S8. How will you continue? 

You know that both East and South are now void of \Ss. You might just switch suits, but you have a better choice.

If you play your \SQ, East won't bother ruffing, South <b>WILL</b> ruff and dummy's \SJ will be established as a winner.

The best procedure is to lead a low \S. East will ruff and South will over-ruff but by playing this way you stop the establishment of North's \SJ. As you can see, South would have been able to discard a loser on that \SJ if you hadn't played this way.}
[Play "W"]SA

